<FeaturePage
  tagline="FEATURE // SECURITY"
  title="AI Agent API Key Security"
  description="API keys never enter LLM context, audit logs, or shell history. Resolved from platform keychain at call time. All output masked."
  relatedPages={relatedPages}
>
  <h2>The guarantee</h2>
  <p>
    Secret values never appear in the LLM context window. The kernel resolves keys from the platform keychain (macOS Keychain, Linux secret-tool) at call time and injects them via subprocess environment variables. The agent sees the tool succeed but never sees the key.
  </p>

  <h2>Output masking</h2>
  <p>
    All tool output passes through <code>secrets::mask()</code> before the LLM sees it. If a secret value appears anywhere — Bash output, file reads, error messages, env dumps — it gets replaced with <code>sk-ant-●●●● (48 chars)</code>. Prefix preserved, length hinted, value hidden.
  </p>

  <h2>Authorization</h2>
  <p>
    The <code>SECRET &lt;&lt;KEYS</code> heredoc in your HUMANFILE is the only place where API keys are authorized for agent use. If a key isn't listed, agents cannot access it — even if it exists in your system keychain.
  </p>

  <h2>BYO vault</h2>
  <p>
    Set <code>OSTK_SECRET_CMD</code> to your preferred secret manager — Bitwarden CLI, 1Password CLI, <code>pass</code>, or any command that takes a key name and returns the value on stdout. The kernel calls it transparently.
  </p>
</FeaturePage>
